    "narrative_summary": "The TP53 c.666G>A substitution (p.Pro222=) is a synonymous change located in exon 6 of the TP53 tumor\u2011suppressor gene. It has been reported in germline screening studies of cancer cohorts and is listed in ClinVar as a likely benign variant, with no established disease association beyond its detection in sporadic tumor sequencing panels.\nIn clinical databases and cohort analyses the variant is consistently interpreted as non\u2011pathogenic. An Iranian lung\u2011cancer series described it as a novel benign variant in their patient set, and a Japanese case\u2011control study of breast\u2011cancer susceptibility classified it as benign in their supplementary data. ClinVar also records the variant as likely benign based on multiple submitters and provided criteria [PMC6061986][PMC6172276][PMC6672031]. Additional tumor\u2011sequencing reports from chordoma and osteosarcoma cohorts list the alteration among somatic coding changes but do not assign any clinical significance, further indicating a lack of pathogenic interpretation in those contexts [PMC5638846][PMC5490007].\nNo functional assays or experimental studies directly assessing the impact of c.666G>A on TP53 protein function were identified in the extracted literature. One supplementary analysis of termination\u2011codon evolution erroneously annotated the change as a nonsense mutation (p.W222*) introducing a premature stop codon, but the report did not provide functional data or a pathogenicity claim, and this annotation conflicts with the synonymous nature of the variant reported elsewhere [PMC10471768].\nPopulation data show the variant is present at a low allele frequency (approximately 6.7\u202f\u00d7\u202f10\u207b\u2075) in public databases (rs72661118) [PMC6061986], consistent with a rare germline polymorphism rather than a recurrent pathogenic mutation. No computational prediction scores were supplied in the extracted sources.\nOverall, the preponderance of evidence from clinical classification databases and cancer\u2011cohort surveys supports a benign or likely benign interpretation of TP53 c.666G>A. The isolated report of a nonsense annotation represents a mischaracterization rather than functional evidence of deleterious effect. Consequently, the variant is best regarded as a non\u2011pathogenic synonymous change with no current implication for disease risk.",
